 America Theme Parks (Atlanta)]]\n|{{N/A|Unknown}}\n|{{yes|Open}}\n|\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://funspotamericaatlanta.com/spider/|title=Spider|date=2017-08-01|website=Fun Spot America Atlanta|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Spider\n|Spider\n|[[Idora Park (Youngstown)|Idora Park]]\n|1973\n|{{no|Closed}}\n|\n|<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n|Spider\n|Spider\n|[[Luna Park, Melbourne]]\n|1983\n|{{yes|Open}}\n|Head on top of Spider designed by children's book author [[Leigh Hobbs]] in 2001\n|\n|-\n|Spider\n|Spider\n|[[Oaks Amusement Park]]\n|{{N/A|Unknown}}\n|{{yes|Open}}\n|\n|\n|-\n|Spider\n|Spider\n|[[Six Flags New England]]\n|1968\n|{{no|2006}}\n|\n|\n|-\n|{{N/A|Unknown}}\n|Spider\n|Jolly Roger at 30th Street\n|{{N/A|Unknown}}\n|{{N/A|Unknown}}\n|\n|\n|-\n|{{N/A|Unknown}}\n|Spider\n|Race City PCB\n|{{N/A|Unknown}}\n|{{N/A|Unknown}}\n|\n|\n|-\n|Monster\n|{{N/A|Unknown}}\n|[[1962 Seattle World's Fair]]\n|{{N/A|Unknown}}\n|{{no|Closed}}\n|Appears similar to a Monster, but only had 5 arms instead of the typical 6.\n|\n|}\n\n== Closure ==\nEyerly Aircraft Company continued to produce amusement rides until 1985.<ref name=\"History-ArgusObserver\">{{cite news |url=http://www.argusobserver.com/news/salem-man-built-carnival-ride-empire/article_50a5e44a-78aa-52fb-92be-b4157b95b39d.html |title=Salem man built carnival ride empire |last=Lynn |first=Capi |newspaper=[[Argus Observer]] |date=August 31, 2008 |accessdate=June 14, 2017}}</ref> A fatal accident occurred at a Florida fair in 1988, where an arm of an Octopus ride snapped along an existing crack that was paint-covered and missed in inspections.<ref name=\"Accident-OrlandoSentinel\" /> A 17-year-old female died of head injuries when the basket she was riding in collided with another as it fell to the ground.<ref name=\"Accident-OrlandoSentinel\">{{cite news |last1=Walker |first1=Donn |title=Fracture Found in Ride That Killed Broward Teen |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-xpm-1988-11-25-0080350284-story.html |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |work=The Orlando Sentinel |date=November 25, 1988}}</ref><ref name=\"AccidentLawsuit-SunSentinel\" /> A wrongful death lawsuit was brought against the ride's owner and county fair operator for failure to properly inspect and reinforce the ride.<ref name=\"FloridaLawsuit-UPI\">{{cite web |title=Family of girl killed at youth fair sues for $10 million |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1988/12/08/Family-of-girl-killed-at-youth-fair-sues-for-10-million/2144597560400/ |publisher=UPI Archives |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |date=December 8, 1988}}</ref><ref name=\"AccidentLawsuit-SunSentinel\">{{cite news |last1=Banker |first1=Dana |title=U.S. Says Ride Owner Knew of Danger |url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1989-05-24-8901270020-story.html |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |work=Sun Sentinel |date=May 24, 1989}}</ref> In the wake of the lawsuit, Eyerly Aircraft filed for bankruptcy and closed its doors permanently in 1990.<ref name=\"History-ArgusObserver\" /> The intellectual property rights to their rides were later purchased by Oregon Rides Inc.<ref name=\"la-rocko\" />\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Aviation|Companies}}\n* [[Octopus (ride)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n[[Category:Amusement ride manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Salem, Oregon]]\n[[Category:1930 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies established in 1930]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies disestablished in 1985]]\n[[Category:1985 disestablishments in Oregon]]\n", "name_user": "Mullins.170", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAmusement rides:Added Spider at Arnolds Park", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eyerly_Aircraft_Company"}
{"title_page": "Mi Gente (J Balvin and Willy William song)", "text_new": "{{short description|2017 single by J. Balvin and Willy William}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Mi Gente\n| cover      = J Balvin Mi Gente.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[J Balvin]] and [[Willy William]]\n| album      = [[Vibras (album)|Vibras]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2017|06|30|df=yes}}\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   = 2017\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Moombahton]]|[[reggaeton]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://time.com/4962254/beyonce-mi-gente-puerto-rico-mexico/|title=Beyonc\u00e9 Just Dropped a New Version of J. rBalvin's 'Mi Gente' to Benefit Hurricane Victims|work=Time|last=Hincks|first=Joseph|date=29 September 2017|accessdate=12 October 2017}}</ref>}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=09}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Scorpio Music|Scorpio]]|[[Universal Music Latin Entertainment|Universal Latin]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[J Balvin|Jos\u00e9 Osorio]]|[[Willy William]]|[[DJ Assad|Adam Assad]]|Andr\u00e9s David Restrepo|[[Mohombi|Mohombi Nzasi Moupondo]]}}\n| producer   = Willy William\n| chronology = [[J Balvin]]\n| prev_title = Bonita\n| prev_year  = 2017\n| next_title = [[Sensualidad (song)|Sensualidad]]\n| next_year  = 2017\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Willy William]]\n | type       = singles\n | prev_title = Voodoo Song\n | prev_year  = 2017\n | title      = Mi Gente\n | year       = 2017\n | next_title = Me Gusta\n | next_year  = 2018\n}}{{External music video|{{YouTube|wnJ6LuUFpMo|\"Mi Gente\"}}}}\n}}\n\"'''Mi Gente'''\" ({{lang-en|My People}}) is a song recorded by Colombian singer [[J Balvin]] and French singer and producer [[Willy William]]. It was released on 30 June 2017 through [[Scorpio Music]] and [[Universal Music Latin Entertainment|Universal Music Latin]]. It is a remix of Willy William's song \"Voodoo Song\". The single was serviced to United States [[contemporary hit radio]] on 18 July 2017.<ref name=\"us radio\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allaccess.com/top40-mainstream/future-releases|title=Top 40/M Future Releases|publisher=All Access|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717194516/https://www.allaccess.com/top40-mainstream/future-releases|archivedate=July 17, 2017|accessdate=July 18, 2017}}</ref> A remix version featuring [[Beyonc\u00e9]] was released on 28 September 2017. J Balvin and Willy William released six more \"Mi Gente\" remixes on 20 October 2017 with [[Steve Aoki]], [[Alesso]], [[Cedric Gervais]], [[Dillon Francis]], [[Sunnery James & Ryan Marciano]], and Henry Fong.\n\n==Composition==\n\"Mi Gente\" is a reworking of Willy William's previous single \"Voodoo Song\", where tune is inspired from the song [[Tokyo Drift (Fast & Furious) (song)|Tokyo Drift (Fast & Furious)]] by [[Teriyaki Boyz]].\n\n==Commercial performance==\nThe original version topped the charts in most Latin American countries.\n\nIn the United States, the original version of the song peaked at number two on the [[Hot Latin Songs]] chart and at number 19 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].\n\nIn Canada, the remix version of the song featuring Beyonce peaked at number 2 on the [[Canadian Hot 100]] and number 3 on the [[Billboard Hot 100]] in the US.\n\n[[J Balvin]] and [[Willy William]] dropped six additional \"Mi Gente\" remixes with [[Steve Aoki]], [[Alesso]], [[Cedric Gervais]], [[Dillon Francis]], [[Sunnery James & Ryan Marciano]], and Henry Fong.<ref name = \"Mi Gente remixes\">{{cite web|url= https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8006819/j-balvin-mi-gente-remixes-steve-aoki-cedric-gervais-dillon-francis|title= J Balvin Drops Six New 'Mi Gente' Remixes With Steve Aoki, Cedric Gervais, Dillon Francis & More|work= billboard.com|accessdate=October 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nDirected by 36 Grados, the accompanying [[music video]] premiered on [[Vevo]] the same day of the single release. [[Leila Cobo]] from ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' magazine described the video as \"an explosion of color and dance\" which features people from around the globe and that is all about unifying through music. It has many cameo appearances, including Italian millionaire Gianluca Vacchi.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7850080/j-balvin-video-mi-gente|title=Watch J Balvin's New (Fantastic) Video 'Mi Gente'|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|first=Leila|last=Cobo|date=30 June 2017|accessdate=7 July 2017}}</ref>\n \nThe music video has over 2.6 billion views on YouTube as of January 2020,<ref>{{cite web|title=J. Balvin, Willy William \u2013 Mi Gente (Official Video)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wnJ6LuUFpMo |publisher=YouTube|accessdate=September 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.noticiasrcn.com/entretenimiento-musica/mi-gente-j-balvin-alcanzo-un-billon-vistas-youtube|title='Mi gente' de J Balvin alcanz\u00f3 un bill\u00f3n de vistas en YouTube|date=2017-10-11|work=Noticias RCN|access-date=2017-10-12|language=es}}</ref> making it the [[List of most viewed YouTube videos|21st most viewed video on the site]]. The video won an MTV VMA  <ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8471501/j-balvin-first-vma-japan-instagram |title = J Balvin Celebrates His First VMA Win in Japan: Watch}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\n\nShortly after the song's release, many listeners noticed a very similar resemblance to [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]]'s [[grito]], first appearing at 0:52 on the record, and twice more throughout the duration of the 3:09 track. The issue became very mainstream, with many reporters falsely believing that the grito was of Pitbull, which it was indeed not. Pitbull's first action was releasing a remix to the record, including his own grito, titling the track \"Mi Gente [Worldwide Remix]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lyrics.com/lyric-lf/1379568/Willy+William/Mi+Gente+%5BWorldwide+Remix%5D|title=Mi Gente [Worldwide Remix]|date=2017-08-10|work=Noticias RCN|access-date=2020-04-18|language=es}}</ref>. After being released, many fans saw the striking resemblance between the two gritos being used. The Pitbull remix intentionally used both Pitbull's and that of the original track to show the similarity.\n\nOn October 8, 2019, Pitbull's legal team applied for a trademark on the popular \"EEEEEEYOOOOOO!\" grito, most popularly brought to market by Pitbull. On April 17, 2020, Pitbull was able to acquire a full trademark to the grito, thus becoming one of the less than 250 owners of a trademark for solely a sound.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/miami-com/miami-com-news/article242059686.html|title=\u2018EEEEEEEYOOOOOO\u2019: Pitbull trademarks his yell. The music industry may never be the same|date=2020-04-17|work=Miami Herald|access-date=2020-04-18|language=es}}</ref> With this, the \"EEEEEEYOOOOOO!\" found in \"Mi Gente\" can no longer be copied or parodied in anyway without legal permission from Pitbull. This prevents the rerelease of the song, or any remix for that matter, to be published with that sound, unless it is removed, or permission is granted from Pitbull.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = Digital download<ref name=\"original\">{{Cite news |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/mi-gente-single/id1251246163 |title=Mi Gente \u2013 Single |website=iTunes (US)}}</ref>\n| title1          = Mi Gente\n| note1           = \n| length1         = 3:09\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = Remix<ref name=\"Henry Fong\">{{Cite news |url= https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/mi-gente-henry-fong-remix-single/id1296043196 |title= Mi Gente (Henry Fong Remix) \u2013 Single|website=iTunes (US)}}</ref>\n| title1          = Mi Gente\n| note1           = Henry Fong Remix\n| length1         = 3:38\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = Remix<ref name=\"H&Q\">{{Cite news |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/mi-gente-